Add new option to disable cpu sync for tensors

Issue: When chaining tensors, there is no need to require output tensors to be copied back from gpu resources to the cpu. It only slows down and introduces another unnecessary copy. While is is normally desired so that the tensor object has cpu accessors that are able to quickly return results, for chaining this is not desired.

title: Bug fix for per layer ORTModule wrap in T5
body:
**Description**: when wrapping T5 encoder/decoder by layer, ORTModule throws the error during training:
AssertionError: ORT found the 6-th module output 'output-6' is non-differentiable according to the onnx graph. However, the gradient value is still provided by PyTorch's autograd engine.

**Motivation and Context**
- The issue can be reproduced with 2 layers of encoders/decoders. And it's specific to decoders. Let's say we have two layers of decoders. In forward pass, an output (requires_grad=False) in the first layer becomes the input of second layer. But its requires_grad becomes True, which is inconsistent (thus incorrect) with Torch's behavior. Therefore it's causing the exception above later on in backward pass.

In most cases, this won't happen. But in some cases where the tensor has been manipulated (re-assign, overwritten, etc.) in the first layer, the requires_flag may be assigned to True by default with torch.autograd extension - see Torch's doc for more details - https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/notes/extending.html#extending-torch-autograd .

The solution is to check _graph_info.output_grad_indices_non_differentiable and mark the tensor with correct requires_grad flag by calling mark_non_differentiable() before the outputs returned back to torch.

title: optimize variadic elementwise ops
body:
**Description**: Optimizer variadic elementwise ops

For cases like this, 12 layers, reusing the same weights. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/127147598-8c0dd2b8-ebf0-4f45-8b76-9553d6bfad63.png)

In PyTorch, after each PythonOpGrad executes, it will accumulate the grad into a buffer (except the first step), so 11 elementwise operator.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/127149121-fb62f97a-d9e3-441f-87ea-85d0f59d7223.png)

In ORT, we will do the gradient sum with a Sum operator at the end, check the part the green arrow points to. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/127149342-9d605708-7338-49d3-80fb-4c089742d35d.png)

If we take a closer look: 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/127149457-4520cbab-8913-4536-ab79-8fda83dc6afb.png)

This is a cuda memset + 12 binary element wise operator. 

Though we could do something to align our scheduling with PyTorch's for better memory usage. But this PR only trying to change "a cuda memset (1.12ms) + 12 binary element wise operator (47.278ms)" to "a cuda memcpy (2.75ms) + 11 binary element wise operator (43.16ms)".e.g. 48.398ms v.s.  45.91ms, 5.14% kernel overhead reduction for this case.



**Motivation and Context**

title: Optimize ARM64EC build
body:
**Description**: The ARM64EC variant of onnxruntime.dll is used to support x64 binaries running on Windows 11 + ARM64. The build has been using a mix of ARM32 intrinsic and default scalar kernels. The existing ARM64 assembly kernels cannot be used as-is because the ARM64EC sandbox: only half the NEON registers are allowed to be used at this time (x13/x14 are also off limits).

This PR adapts versions of the ARM64 kernels to the above restrictions. The qgemm kernel is roughly a port back of the NEON aarch32 kernel which also only had 16 NEON registers to work with.

The UDOT kernel will be ported in a subsequent update to further improve performance on Surface X.

title: Configuring ORTModule - Internal Options
body:
This pull request introduces a way to load configuration options in ```ORTModule``` from a json file. Configurable options include:
- Propagate cast ops
- Use external GPU allocator
- Enable custom auto grad function
- Allow layer norm mod precision
- Enable grad acc optimization
- Use static shape
- Run symbolic shape inference
- Skip check
- Debug options

To load configuration from json to ```ORTModule```, users can use the function ```load_from_json``` from inside the experimental namespace.
```py
from onnxruntime.training.ortmodule.experimental.json_config import load_from_json

# Instantiate ORTModule
model = ORTModule(pt_model)

# Load config from json
load_from_json(model, path=path_to_json)
```

Alternately, users can also set the environment variable ```ORTMODULE_JSON_CONFIG_PATH``` to the json path and avoid referencing the json path in the python script.

This pull request also includes a sample test that loads configuration from an example json file (for reference).

title: Fix attention parity for GPT-2
body:
**Description**: 

Update attention operator to be in parity with huggingface GPT-2 & PyTorch.
(1) Use huggingface logic for unidirectional (causal) mask. Previous implementation add -10000.0, and huggingface will replace the value with -10000.0 for causal mask. This impacts the value of words masked by attention mask, and has slight impact on non masked words.
(2) Use persistent softmax in cuda to have same result as PyTorch. This seems to be major cause of fp16 difference.

After this change, CUDA result is 100% same. However CPU result still have slight difference from GEMM output.

For testing, add an environment variable (ORT_TRANSFORMER_OPTIONS=1 or 2) to enable/disable persistent softmax in attention.

title: (WIP) [js/web] WebGL backend refactor
body:
**Description**: This PR contains several changes to the WebGL backend framework code. The major changes are:
- [x] unify concepts `ProgramInfo` and `RunData` for operator implementations. Previously it's designed based on the assumption that each operator will be implemented by using exactly 1 WebGL shader program, which is proved to be false. The old operator interface is replaced by a function-based one, using `WebGLInferenceHandler.run()` to run a program, which can be called multiple times in one operator's implementation.
- [x] remove `createProgramInfo` and `createRunData` and use one implementation function.
- [x] operator resolves to the implementation function ( instead of the instance based Operator interface)
- [x] Hide TextureLayout and TextureData from operator implementation. Now they are WebGL backend internal data structures.
- [ ] introduce `ProgramInfoLoader` for caching reusable program info. (WIP)

The behavior should not be changed before vs. after the refactoring.

Benefit of this change:
- operators are much easier to develop (ie. implement new operator, or maintain existing ones), because of the simplification on interfaces and concepts.
- artifacts cache will work as expected for all programs. (before this refactoring, the cache breaks when multiple shader programs are used in one operator implementation. )
- cleaned up blockers for some future features (eg. texture based const-folding)

title: Memory aware gradient builder.
body:
Introduces a gradient graph builder feature to keep reference count (in backward pass) of activations produces in the forward pass. Using the reference count we can automatically substitute layer norm gradient operator for its corresponding invertible operator to reduce peak memory by not stashing inputs to the gradient operator from forward pass if there are no references in the backward pass. 

Using this change we see a reduction of peak memory in the forward pass by ~500MB on BERT-L, although we also see reduction in throughput/compute by 1-2% because invertible layer norm operator does slightly more computation as it takes a dependency on gamma/beta (bias) variables that also incurs memory reads.

title: Optimize sequence type usage on CUDA [1/n]
body:
**Description**:

Generally speaking, we tend to keep inputs/outputs of CUDA operators that are "semantically" tied to shape/shape processing on CPU (for example, indices). The advantage is two-fold:

1) While specifying that such inputs/outputs be placed on CPU in the kernel definition, it helps the force fallback logic take such hints to place related neighboring shape nodes feeding/consuming such edges on CPU. This avoids introducing a copy to device.

2) After consuming such inputs (or while producing such outputs), the CUDA kernel internally does not need to do a copy to host to bring such data to the host (write such data to the host). This avoid introducing a copy to host.  

By not doing this, it a "double whammy" - we will see 2 copies - one to take such information "semantically" tied to the host to the device for the CUDA kernel and another copy within the kernel to take it back to the host at kernel processing time. This change avoids such inefficiencies.

**Motivation and Context**
Found while tuning CUDA EP perf for a 1P model

title: Handle duplicated outputs in eval mode and under torch.no_grad context
body:
In ```eval``` mode and under ```torch.no_grad()``` context, ```ORTModule``` uses the ```inference_agent``` which uses ```IOBinding``` to execute the graph. ```IOBinding``` only registers a single output for duplicate output names. As a result, when the model has duplicated outputs, the returned values from the ORT backend will only correspond to the ones registered through ```IOBinding```.

This pull request introduces a mapping for output names to the index of the ORT outputs. And so adds support for duplicated outputs in the user model.

**Description**: 
The purpose of this PR is to provide a way to define ONNX schema and register such schemas in to onnxruntime in python environment. The onnx::* symbols used in the custom ops shared library need to be resolved at load time from the onnx, onnx_proto libraries. The custom ops shared library (implemented as a shared library may be implemented in C/C++) may be loaded and resolved in a couple of ways:

1. Using session_options.register_custom_ops_library function (https://dev.azure.com/sajandhy/custom_ops/_git/custom_ops)

title: Dnnl refactor
body:
**Description**:
This is a rework of the DNNL execution provider.

`DnnlTensor`, `DnnlNode`, and `DnnlSubgraph` have been updated to support arbitrary graph topology and tensor data types. The previous version of the DNNL execution provider only supported F32 data types.

rework `GetCapability` to claim nodes in graph greedily from node topological ordering and delay creation of `DnnlSubgraph` until Compile

rework compile to have `DnnlSubgraphPrimitive` as the object to handle primitive creation and execution instead of thread-local primitive pool which duplicated intermediate memory allocated by the execution provider across threads.

`DnnlSubgraphPrimitive` provides helpers to handle many common functions for each DNNL primitive builder and become the centralized place to:
- store input , output, intermediate memory, initializer memory, etc
- it provides functions to obtain input memories with automatic reordering/reshaping and moving between DNNL engines
- it provides interfaces to add primitive, set output memory for each node, etc
- Improved initializer caching

add `CONCURRENT_EXEC` compile flag for DNNL library as, without it, convolution primitive cannot be created and executed on different threads

Enable unit tests to run on DNNL execution provider as well if built with DNNL execution provider



Updated the following Operators for the reworked execution provider:
- AveragePool
- BatchNorm
- Conv
- ConvGrad
- GlobalAveragePool
- GlobalMaxPool
- LRN
- MatMul
- MaxPoolGrad
- MaxPool
- ReduceMean
- Relu
- ReluGrad
- Sum

Implemented new operators:
- Add
- AveragePoolGrad
- Div
- MatMulInteger
- Mul
- SoftMax
- Sub


**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?

This PR solves several major issues:
- It make it possible to support more than just the Float32 data type.
- It improves DNNL subgraph generation:
    - It takes the topology of the graph into consideration more than the previous code
    - a subgraph can support more than one output.
- Memory (inputs, outputs, and reorders) are now handle in the `DnnlSubgraphPrimitive` removing the need to handle those in each operator.
    - This reduces need to worry about the DNNL engine (i.e. CPU vs. GPU) when writing each operator
    - Simplifies code size for each operator for example Relu went from 207 lines to 70, Conv went from 777 lines to 478.
- better code verification via unit test since the default unit tests now run the DNNL execution provider if the dnnl build flag is provided.

title: constrain inputs for min/max grad UT
body:
**Description**: Fix the input values for MinMaxGradient UT.

**Motivation and Context**
`Min(x1, x2)` is not smooth when `x1` equals `x2`. The original test case uses randomly generated inputs.
When the generated inputs are close enough (|difference| < 1e-3f, the delta value), calculating NumericJacobian will get wrong values, causing the UT to fail.
e.g. `x1=1.0, x2=1.0005, y=min(x1, x2)`. Gradient should be (1.0, 0.0), but the numeric gradient will be (0.75, 0.25):
- numeric gradient w.r.t. `x1` is: `[min(x1+0.001, x2) - min(x1-0.001, x2)]/0.002 = (1.0005-0.999)/0.002 = 0.75`
- numeric gradient w.r.t. `x2` is: `[min(x1, x2+0.001) - min(x1, x2-0.001)]/0.002 = (1.0-0.9995)/0.002 = 0.25`

Likewise for `Max(x1, x2)`.

This change is to avoid such cases and hence occasional CI failures.

title: Fix location planning for initializers used only in nested subgraphs
body:
**Description**: The current logic for planning the location for all initializers at a graph level only involves walking the nodes at that graph level. This is incomplete as the initializers could actually be used in any of the nested subgraphs relative to that graph level. We need to walk all the nested subgraphs to have the necessary information needed to decide the correct location that the initializers needs to reside on.

The negative impact of not doing this is that if the initializers were only used in one of the nested subgraphs (not used in the graph level they are introduced in) and used in a provider node (e.g. CUDA), with the current logic keeping these initializers on CPU, the controlflow nodes' implementation takes them from CPU to the device at runtime (and the impact is much worse for Loops as these copies are done on every iteration). 

This change adds logic to walk all the nested subgraphs while processing initializers at a given graph level and take them statically to the right device thus saving all the runtime copies. 

**Motivation and Context**
~50% gains for a 1P model. Should also benefit other models having a similar structure.
